solidarity leader lech walesa left for 
warsaw on wednesday for his first talks with polish authorities 
since solidarity was banned the government hoped the meeting would 
end two weeks of labor unrest 
asked what he would discuss with interior minister gen czeslaw 
kiszczak during the talks walesa said how to make up for the 
past seven years solidarity was crushed in a 1981 military 
crackdown 
walesa traveled by car with senior solidarity adviser tadeusz 
mazowiecki 
the meeting walesas advisers said would be held wednesday would 
follow four days of maneuvering started by kiszczaks proposal on 
