<TEXT>
prime time tv characters this fall will begin 
turning down drinks in a coordinated assault on drunken driving 
initiated by harvard university health researchers 
makebelieve wives will designate makebelieve husbands as 
nondrinking drivers teenagers who drink will take taxis and for 
the next few years polltakers will be trying to find out if viewers 
are coming under the influence of the push for a designated 
driver 
the goal of the project is to achieve a fundamental change in 
american social norms regarding drinking and driving jay 
winsten assistant dean of harvards school of public health and 
director of its center for health communication said tuesday night 
in attempting to achieve that change were asking the 
entertainment communication and advertising industries to work 
with us to add momentum behind changes that are already beginning 
to occur in america he said of the harvard alcohol project 
winsten said the commitment was made by 13 television studios in 
los angeles that are responsible for more than 70 percent of prime 
time weekly programming on abc cbs and nbc 
the executives pledged to ask their writers and producers to 
introduce in their scripts the notion that drinking and driving is 
taboo through devices as simple as having drinkers take taxis or 
saying no thanks im driving 
winsten said if the television campaign succeeds others will be 
tried but drunken driving was the priority he said reciting 
these statistics drunken driving kills 24000 people each year 
studies show as few as two drinks can make a fatal accident twice 
as likely two of five americans will be victims of a drunken 
driver 
in january winsten began meeting with hollywood executives to 
forge the agreements in april he won a unanimous endorsement from 
the board of the writers guild of americawest whose members write 
for prime time tv 
the networks also agreed to run public service announcements in 
december to encourage the designated driver idea the new york 
times reported today 
the new york advertising firm saatchi amp saatchi dfs compton 
has provided advertising research on the designated driver idea 
and the gallup organization said it will donate its services to 
poll the public to find out whether the tv campaign is working the 
newspaper said 
gallup research shows that 78 percent of all drivers would be 
willing to serve occasionally as designated drivers 
winsten said the campaign will continue for at least three to 
five years before its real impact will be known 
the campaign has precedents he said television networks during 
the past year or two have been using their characters to encourage 
the use of seatbelts and to try to take the glamour out of alcohol 
but winsten said he believed this was the first such effort 
mobilized by a school of public health 
