<TEXT>
banter between the pilots of a continental jet 
before it crashed nov 15 killing 28 people apparently violated 
federal regulations officials say 
a previously undisclosed portion of the black box cockpit 
recording from the dc9 shows that in the minutes before flight 
1713 crashed the pilots discussed the dating habits of a woman 
flight attendant and other matters unrelated to the flight 
the tape shows the pilots did not discuss the snow falling at 
stapleton international airport 
both pilots flight captain frank zvonek and copilot lee edward 
bruecher were killed in the crash fiftyfour people were injured 
a federal aviation administration rule known as the sterile 
cockpit concept prohibits nonessential conversation in the 
cockpit during ground operations and takeoff preparations 
faa spokesman dick meyer said a pilot who violated the rule 
could be suspended or fined as much as 10000 
that would definitely be extraneous meyer said tuesday of 
the discussions between the two pilots the main point is the 
cockpit crew is supposed to be concentrating on their primary 
business of flying the airplane distractions can be deadly 
the faa enacted the regulation in the late 1970s or early 1980s 
after several instances where we found in accidents where flight 
crews were talking about something other than flying the 
airplane faa spokesman fred farrar said 
continental spokesman bruce hicks said nonpertinent 
conversations are common among pilots if the pilots on 1713 were 
in violation of that reg 999 percent of all commercial pilots in 
history have violated that reg he said 
hicks had said previously that the pilots maintained a highly 
skilled welldisciplined professional cockpit 
the pilots conversation has become an issue as the national 
transportation safety board studies possible causes of the 
accident which occurred in a snowstorm 
mel hoagland who retired as a united airlines dc10 captain 
this month said such cockpit conversations arent unusual you 
cant just sit and be keyed right on the edge of the aviation 
experiences all of the time he said 
ed arbon vice president of the flight safety foundation of 
arlington va said that unless pilots anticipate a waiting 
period it is unusual for them to spend much time discussing 
nonflight matters in a plane prpearing to take off in snow 
if the weathers of concern usually your attention is taken 
up by the business at hand he said 
the ntsb is to meet next month to review the accident the board 
is studying whether ice or snow buildup on the wings the 
experience and training of the pilots and possible turbulence from 
another aircraft caused the crash 
