<TEXT>
the boston symphony orchestra did not violate the 
civil rights of actress vanessa redgrave when it canceled her 
performances following threats by protesters a federal appeals 
court ruled wednesday 
the full us 1st circuit court of appeals ruled by a 32 vote 
that the cancellation did not violate the massachusetts civil 
rights act it was an unusual reversal of an earlier finding by a 
threemember panel of the appellate court 
wednesdays decision reinstated an award to compensate ms 
redgrave 12000 she would have earned in a broadway role she lost 
during the suit against the symphony however expenses the actress 
would have incurred while appearing in the play will be subtracted 
from the award 
orchestra attorney bob sullivan said symphony officials were 
relieved with the ruling 
i think theyre also happy that the case is probably over now 
and they can go back to doing what theyre best at making 
music he said 
attorneys for ms redgrave daniel j kornstein and marvin 
wexler of new york were not in their offices and did not return 
calls wednesday evening 
ms redgrave was hired by the symphony in 1982 to narrate six 
performances of stravinskys oedipus rex at boston tanglewood 
in western massachusetts and new yorks carnegie hall 
but the contract was canceled after the symphony received 
letters and telephone calls indicating there would be picketing and 
other protests because of ms redgraves support of the palestine 
liberation organization 
in november 1984 a federal jury ruled the symphony had breached 
its contract with ms redgrave and awarded her the 27500 she was 
to have received for the performances plus 100000 in compensatory 
damages for work the actress said she lost because of the action 
in february 1985 us district judge robert keeton threw out 
the 100000 award and ruled the symphony had not violated her 
civil rights 
last october a threemember panel of the us 1st circuit court 
of appeals restored 12000 of that award as compensation for the 
lost role the threemember panel also found the massachusetts 
civil rights act had been violated 
attorneys for the symphony arguing that massachusetts law 
allowed them to cancel performances because of concerns that 
threatened disruptions would mar the artistic integrity of the 
performances asked for a rehearing before the full court 
wednesdays ruling by the full court effectively reversing the 
earlier finding was unusual sullivan said 
this is a very very rare thing he said the 1st circuit 
very seldom reverses themselves 
