<TEXT>
backed by a broad new law new jersey is 
trying to seize control of a major urban school district it 
considers to be educationally bankrupt 
state officials say schools in jersey city new jerseys second 
largest city are so crippled by political patronage that local 
leaders cannot make desperately needed improvements 
symptomatic they say are curricula on afroamerican history 
that end with the nixon administration 
city officials disagree and are trying to block the takeover 
jersey city is providing the first test of a law enacted in 
january giving new jersey power to take over chronically troubled 
schools 
kentucky south carolina texas and new mexico have laws of 
varying strength allowing state takeovers of failing school 
districts according to the national governors association laws in 
illinois and arkansas let the state eliminate deficient districts 
and an ohio law allows the state to revoke a districts charter a 
georgia law allows financial penalties in the form of reduced state 
aid 
if new jersey wins it can abolish the local board of education 
fire administrators and appoint a state superintendent to operate 
the district of 32000 students for five years 
when schools fail its adults who failed and adults should 
pay the price gov thomas kean said when he signed the law 
jersey city officials say their city suffers from the poverty 
and crime typical of urban districts they contend that to single 
out jersey city for state takeover is unfair when efforts are being 
made to reverse the decay from years of political intrusion under 
former administrations 
the state launched the takeover in may after almost three years 
of investigation and monitoring in the district 
i dont think they were looking for anything right they were 
on a mission to point up what was wrong said william massa 
attorney for the jersey city board of education 
takeover hearings before an administrative law judge are 
expected to last into january the earliest the state could take 
control is next may but appeals by the district could further 
delay action 
state investigators said they found financial irregularities 
questionable payroll and personnel practices and incompetent 
management richard kaplan the states lead investigator said 
district employees are routinely rewarded or demoted based on which 
mayoral candidate they backed in the most recent election 
they also cited low test scores and high truancy rates last 
year jersey city students registered the third lowest passing rate 
in the state on a mandatory statewide ninthgrade test 
eleven other new jersey districts including newark are in the 
third and final stage of state monitoring that precedes a takeover 
six of the districts are working with the state to make 
improvements and officials hope the jersey city action sends a 
signal that new jersey is ready to act again if a district fails to 
make the grade 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

