<TEXT>
jc penney company inc has borrowed 700 million 
to create a leveraged employee stock ownership plan in conjunction 
with an expanded stock buyback program the retailing company 
announced tuesday 
the socalled lesop a taxqualified employee benefit trust that 
invests in the sponsoring companys securities will replace jc 
penneys existing employee savings and profitsharing retirement 
plan 
penney employees already own 15 percent of the companys 132 
million common shares outstanding through their existing retirement 
plan 
the lesop is using the proceeds of the 700 million loan to 
purchase a new issue of convertible preferred stock from the 
company officials said the preferred stock is convertible into 
about 118 million shares of the companys common stock about 9 
percent of the currently outstanding common shares 
penney will use the 700 million it gets from the employee trust 
to buy back 15 million common shares from the public therefore 
the employees will end up controlling 316 million common shares 
or about 245 percent of the common shares that ultimately will be 
outstanding 
william r howell penneys chairman said the plan would help 
boost shareholder value 
we see these steps as strengthening the interests of our major 
constituencies our investors our consumers and our associates 
employees 
it wont really have an effect on our daytoday operation 
said company spokesman harvey mccormick as far as long term it 
should boost our earnings per share reduce costs and increase our 
cash flow 
such employee stock ownership plans commonly have been 
implemented by corporations anxious to place a large block of their 
shares into friendly hands thus helping thwart potential raids 
penneys plan is the largest such lesop yet created according to 
some reports 
penney said it would redirect its annual contribution from the 
savings plan to the lesop last year those contributions were 50 
million 
penney stock rose 187 a share to 4812 tuesday on the new 
york stock exchange 
</TEXT>
