<TEXT>
senior bank of japan officials indicated that the 
central bank has no plans to raise its discount rate despite recent 
interestrate hikes in europe and the united states 
at a briefing wednesday for japanese reporters bank officials 
said it is part of the central banks contribution to international 
policy coordination not to push up the key interest rate the 
officials did not elaborate 
the news sent the us dollar up sharply against the japanese 
yen in foreignexchange trading other central bank officials were 
quoted as saying that the bank of japan might have to intervene to 
stop the yens decline 
kyodo news service said bank of japan officials made the remarks 
after the dollar rose above 136 yen in european trading on the 
earlier reports that the japanese central bank would not raise 
rates 
last week west germanys bundesbank raised its discount rate a 
half point and several european banks quickly followed the us 
federal reserve had made a similar move a few weeks earlier 
kyodo quoted some bank of japan officials as saying the 
yendollar rates have reached a level that should be watched very 
carefully and that action might be warranted if new movements in 
the currencies occur 
the remarks appeared to indicate that the bank of japan may 
intervene to brake the dollars rise if the us currency continues 
to advance 
the central bank doesnt want to see the yen slide further 
against the dollar because of concern about higher domestic 
inflation 
the yens sharp appreciation since late 1985 has helped to hold 
down domestic prices but accelerated growth in money supply amid 
the present robust economic expansion and the yens recent downturn 
have spawned worries about inflation 
according to kyodo bank of japan officials said they would 
consider not only the yens levels against the dollar but the pace 
of its decline and the strength of yen selling in deciding whether 
or not to intervene against the dollars rise 
the senior bank of japan officials who indicated that no rate 
hike is in the works described the recent key rate increases by 
the us and european central banks as aimed at fighting inflation 
they said the us and european rate increases honor the 
spirit of policy coordination by the group of seven major 
industrial countries since it advocates stemming inflation in 
order to sustain world economic growth 
the group of seven countries are the united states japan west 
germany britain france canada and italy 
some foreignexchange and moneymarket participants said 
japanese monetary authorities have refrained from raising the 
discount rate because such a move would make japanese funds more 
expensive overseas and may prove counterproductive in keeping the 
global economy on an expansionary track 
japan is a launching pad of investment funds for the world 
the united states and other industrialized countries would do 
whatever they could to keep japan from raising interest rates 
further said an official at chemical bank in tokyo 
