<TEXT>
the european economic community 
wednesday slapped provisional antidumping duties on exports of 
video cassette recorders from south korea and japan after 
complaints by domestic manufacturers 
the duties follow a surge in vcr exports to the eec since 1985 
primarily from south korea who tripled its vcr exports to europe in 
a years time the eec executive commission said 
the duties affect three south korean companies that account for 
all of that countrys vcr exports including daewoo goldstar and 
samsung the japanese companies affected are funai and orion 
the commission said south koreas vcr exports into europe surged 
from 75000 in 1985 to 425000 in 1986 and 122 million last year 
imports from the two japanese companies more than doubled to 
991000 units in 1986 from 466000 in 1985 in the first eight 
months of 1987 762000 funai and orion vcrs entered the eec the 
commission said 
the duties levied include 292 percent for daewoo 264 percent 
for goldstar 252 percent for samsung and 18 percent on funai and 
orion vcrs 
the level of the duties was fixed after a commission inquiry 
into the sharp rise of vcr imports 
the commission began its probe in september 1987 on a complaint 
by an eec industry association representing producers of consumer 
electronics the group complained that vcr imports from the three 
south korean and two japanese firms surged because of their 
artificially low prices 
the groups members include philips international bv of the 
netherlands grundig ag and telefunken fernsehen und rundfunk gmbh 
both of west germany thomson grand public of france and britains 
ferguson plc 
the commission said it found that the south korean and japanese 
companies sold vcrs in the eec at dumping prices or at prices 
considered unfairly low as a result their combined share of the 
eecs vcr market rose to 30 percent last year from 86 percent in 
1985 
since 1985 vcr purchases in the 12nation eec rose to 7 million 
from 58 million european currency units or the equivalent of 77 
from 638 million the commission said 
it concluded the market share gains of the south korean and 
japanese exporters were made at the expense of the eecs vcr 
industry and that their dumping prices lowered the sales and profit 
margins of their eec competitors 
</TEXT>
