and 1960s and will be played out in the 1990s 
the plot is a demographic one a twodecade bulge of americans 
of homebuying age will have passed through the economy leaving a 
still large but substantially smaller demand for lowerpriced 
starter homes 
among the characters affected will be developers lenders 
builders trades people brokers materials suppliers and investors 
they have no choice but to accept that notion and accommodate 
themselves to the reality says james wooten chairman of lomas 
mortgage usa and publisher of us housing markets a subscription 
newsletter 
the latest analysis by the newsletter whose surveys and studies 
are widely accepted in the housing industry offers these 
demographicbased projections 
annual household formations gradually will fall to less than 
twothirds of the 19841987 average 
private housing starts will average no more than 14 million a 
year for most of the decade of the 1990s compared with 2 million 
in 1977 and more than 17 million in the years 19831985 
new housing will shift inexorably toward higher price ranges 
reflecting the greater affluence and grander lifestyles of older 
buyers 
traditional rental apartments aimed at younger tenants will be 
in less demand says wooten landlords will need to find 
innovative products to attract households in higher age brackets 
housing targeted for older americans those retired or 
planning retirement will be find a growing market 
wooten butresses his conclusions with immutable demographic 
evidence 
in 1975 for example nearly 40 million americans were in their 
20s the primary market bracket for apartments and starter homes 
while only 23 million were in the moveup category of 35 years 
to 44 years 
by the end of the century the numbers will almost flipflop with 
more than 43 million individuals in the age 35 to 44 bracket while 
those in their 20s will have contracted to 34 million 
these numbers portend a development that might also have a 
serious impact on those who currently own homes and are relying on 
the equity in them to finance their retirements 
wooten describes the potential phenomenon in this way 
as america ages as the middleyears cohort climbs the ladder 
from first moveup and thence to second third and fourth the lower 
rungs will be holding fewer and fewer potential buyers 
the homes being left behind will be offered to a dwindling 
list of prospects 
thus in overall terms the existinghome market will 
gradually evolve into a buyers market beginning in the lower 
regions of the price spectrum 
the situation wooten describes doesnt dictate lower prices nor 
does it mean that prices cannot increase 
but it strongly suggests that the sharp price increases of the 
1970s and 1980s will be by the year 2000 a thing of the past 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
