because a grand jury is still hearing details he said the 
investigation involves possible criminal wrongdoing including 
violations of the us tax code 
a statement issued by arthur andersen from the companys chicago 
headquarters denied any wrongdoing but georgia power chairman 
robert w scherer speaking for the electric utility and southern 
co said he was shocked by the allegations and vowed to get to 
the bottom of this matter the papers raised the question of 
whether the companies and their accountants sought to hide about 
61 million in spare parts to avoid paying 50 million in federal 
taxes interest and penalties 
key elements in that question are whether parts are classified 
as emergency spares or for maintainence and when they become 
expenses to the company 
the papers also raised the question of georgia powers 
accounting for the sale of 5 percent of the vogtle nuclear power 
plant to the municipal electric authority of georgia 
in the documents officials say the deal was treated as a sale 
of 5 percent of the 887 billion plant for book value purposes 
but as 135 percent for tax purposes saving the company between 
10 million and 12 million 
the papers include excerpts of taped conversations in which 
southern cos tax chief agrees with an informant that the company 
misled the irs over the tax accounting of the spare parts but 
adds dont ever say that 
the investigation dating to 1982 is based largely on 
