<TEXT>
the chicago board options exchange and some of 
its traders overcharged more than 1000 investors who lost at least 
40 million the day after the stock market collapsed a lawyer 
charged wednesday after filing a lawsuit 
the cboe and floor traders responsible for making markets in 
certain options on the standard amp poors 100 stock index violated 
federal law and the exchanges own rules by charging inflated 
prices for options contracts last oct 20 attorney herbert beigel 
alleged in a classaction lawsuit 
the investors were gouged by virtue of being charged excessive 
prices beigel a partner in the chicagobased law firm beigel amp 
sandler said in a telephone interview from his new york office 
the market makers with the assistance of the cboe 
deliberately charged investors very excessive prices which made it 
difficult for the investors to make money because there was not a 
legitimate market 
cboe officials were aware of the lawsuit which consolidates 
three previous classaction lawsuits but would not comment on it 
said spokesman warren moulds 
an option is a contract giving the holder the right to buy or 
sell a commodity or financial instrument for a specific price at a 
future date in the case of sampp 100 index options the item being 
traded is the value of the sampp 100 index which measures the 
performance of 100 stocks 
the price or premium of an index option depends on a number of 
variables including the time until the expiration of the option 
and the volatility of the underlying index 
the cboe the worlds leading options exchange has said the 
doubling and tripling of index options prices on oct 20 were 
understandable in light of the markets unprecedented volatility 
that day 
the exchange also facilitated the collection of 12 million 
earmarked as refunds for investors who paid extremely high prices 
for sampp 100 index options contracts on oct 20 the money was 
collected from traders and distributed to brokerage firms 
but beigel said the refunds amounted to at most 20 percent of 
the total lost by some investors 
the lawsuit filed tuesday in us district court in chicago 
combines and broadens the claims of the three previous lawsuits it 
seeks an amount equal to the money invested less any returns or 
refunds plus an unspecified amount for lost use of the money and 
interest 
it names as plaintiffs all people who purchased oex or 
oezseries index options on oct 20 at the cboe except those who 
acted as market makers for such transactions 
the lawsuit names as defendants the cboe the options clearing 
corp a separate firm that processes trades made at the exchange 
and all cboe floor traders who were designated as market makers for 
the oex and oez series of sampp 100 index options on oct 20 
trading losses in index options on oct 19 and 20 have been 
estimated at several hundred million dollars nationwide index 
options were among the largest sources of investor complaints in 
the weeks after the 508point drop in the dow jones industrial 
average on oct 19 
index options which account for more than half the trading 
volume at the cboe are hedging tools that investors use to protect 
themselves against losses in the stock market 
</TEXT>
